</td></tr><tr><th scope="row">Website</th><td><a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/">http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/</a></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Paul Bloom</b> (born December 24, 1963) is a <a href="/wiki/Canadian_American" class="mw-redirect" title="Canadian American">Canadian American</a> psychologist. He is the Brooks and Suzanne Ragen Professor of <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_science" title="Cognitive science">cognitive science</a> at <a href="/wiki/Yale_University" title="Yale University">Yale University</a>. His research explores how children and adults understand the physical and social world, with special focus on <a href="/wiki/Language_development" title="Language development">language</a>, <a href="/wiki/Morality" title="Morality">morality</a>, <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fiction" title="Fiction">fiction</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Art" title="Art">art</a>.
</p>
